{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599538"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:56:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:56:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.56,0.24,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70164"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8269"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7009"},{"type":"tags","id":"10131"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70164"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe parathyroid glands maintain calcium homeostasis by secreting parathyroid hormone (PTH). This process is tightly regulated by blood calcium levels through calcium-sensing receptors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how calcium regulates parathyroid hormone secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High calcium stimulates PTH secretion via granule fusion","High calcium inhibits both PTH secretion and transcription","High calcium blocks PTH secretion but increases gene transcription","Low calcium suppresses both PTH secretion and transcription","Low calcium prevents granule fusion but increases transcription"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe regulation of PTH by calcium involves both immediate and long-term mechanisms. When \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh calcium\u003C/strong\u003E binds to calcium-sensing receptors, it rapidly inhibits the release of stored PTH by blocking storage granule fusion with the cell membrane. It also reduces PTH gene transcription over hours to days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium stimulates PTH secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as high calcium suppresses PTH release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium blocks secretion but increases transcription\u003C/strong\u003E - Both secretion and transcription are inhibited by high calcium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow calcium suppresses secretion and transcription\u003C/strong\u003E - Low calcium actually stimulates both processes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow calcium prevents granule fusion\u003C/strong\u003E - Low calcium promotes granule fusion for rapid PTH release\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis dual regulation allows both rapid responses through granule fusion and sustained responses through transcriptional control, maintaining tight calcium homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Calcium acts via calcium-sensing receptors to inhibit PTH secretion through blocked granule fusion and reduced gene transcription","Low calcium levels trigger both immediate PTH release and increased PTH gene transcription","This dual regulation allows both rapid and sustained responses to maintain calcium homeostasis"],"references":["Cusano NE, Bilezikian JP. Parathyroid hormone in the evaluation of hypercalcemia. JAMA. 2014 Dec 24-31;312(24):2680-1. doi: 10.1001/jama.2014.9195. PMID: 25536261; PMCID: PMC4308950.","Lofrese JJ, Basit H, Lappin SL. Physiology, Parathyroid. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482510/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15578"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T20:22:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T20:23:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8269"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70164"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"